# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fenwick-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] A **bit array** (also known as **bit map**, **bit set**, **bit string**, or **bit vector**) is an array data structure that compactly stores bits.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] It can be used to implement a simple set data structure.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] A bit array is effective at exploiting bit-level parallelism in hardware to perform operations quickly.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] A typical bit array stores *kw* bits, where *w* is the number of bits in the unit of storage, such as a byte or word, and *k* is some positive integer.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] If *w* does not divide the number of bits to be stored, some space is wasted due to internal fragmentation.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] A bit array is a mapping from some domain (almost always a range of integers) to values in the set $\{{\texttt {0}},{\texttt {1}}\}$ .
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The values can be interpreted as dark/light, absent/present, locked/unlocked, valid/invalid, et cetera.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The point is that there are only two possible values, so they can be stored in one bit.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] As with other arrays, the access to a single bit can be managed by applying an index to the array.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Assuming its size (or length) to be *n* bits, the array can be used to specify a subset of the domain (e.g. $\{0,1,2,...,n-1\}$ ), where a 1-bit indicates the presence and a 0-bit the absence of a number in the set.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] This set data structure uses about *n*/*w* words of space, where *w* is the number of bits in each machine word.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Whether the least significant bit (of the word) or the most significant bit indicates the smallest-index number is largely irrelevant, but the former tends to be preferred (on little-endian machines).
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] A finite binary relation may be represented by a bit array called a logical matrix.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] In the calculus of relations, these arrays are composed with matrix multiplication where the arithmetic is Boolean, and such a composition represents composition of relations.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Although most machines are not able to address individual bits in memory, nor have instructions to manipulate single bits, each bit in a word can be singled out and manipulated using bitwise operations.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] To obtain the bit mask needed for these operations, we can use a bit shift operator to shift the number 1 to the left by the appropriate number of places, as well as bitwise negation if necessary.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] If we wish to iterate through the bits of a bit array, we can do this efficiently using a doubly nested loop that loops through each word, one at a time.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Both of these code samples exhibit ideal locality of reference, which will subsequently receive large performance boost from a data cache.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] If a cache line is *k* words, only about *n*/*wk* cache misses will occur.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] As with character strings it is straightforward to define *length*, *substring*, lexicographical *compare*, *concatenation*, *reverse* operations.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The implementation of some of these operations is sensitive to endianness.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] If we wish to find the number of 1 bits in a bit array, sometimes called the population count or Hamming weight, there are efficient branch-free algorithms that can compute the number of bits in a word using a series of simple bit operations.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] We simply run such an algorithm on each word and keep a running total.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] See the Hamming weight article for examples of an efficient implementation.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Vertical flipping of a one-bit-per-pixel image, or some FFT algorithms, requires flipping the bits of individual words (so `b31 b30 ... b0` becomes `b0 ... b30 b31`).
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The find first set or *find first one* operation identifies the index or position of the 1-bit with the smallest index in an array, and has widespread hardware support (for arrays not larger than a word) and efficient algorithms for its computation.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] When a priority queue is stored in a bit array, find first one can be used to identify the highest priority element in the queue.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] To expand a word-size *find first one* to longer arrays, one can find the first nonzero word and then run *find first one* on that word.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The related operations *find first zero*, *count leading zeros*, *count leading ones*, *count trailing zeros*, *count trailing ones*, and *log base 2* (see find first set) can also be extended to a bit array in a straightforward manner.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] A bit array is the most dense storage for "random" bits, that is, where each bit is equally likely to be 0 or 1, and each one is independent.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] But most data are not random, so it may be possible to store it more compactly.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] For example, the data of a typical fax image is not random and can be compressed.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Run-length encoding is commonly used to compress these long streams.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] However, most compressed data formats are not so easy to access randomly; also by compressing bit arrays too aggressively we run the risk of losing the benefits due to bit-level parallelism (vectorization).
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Thus, instead of compressing bit arrays as streams of bits, we might compress them as streams of bytes or words (see Bitmap index (compression)).
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] However, bit arrays are not the solution to everything.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Because of their compactness, bit arrays have a number of applications in areas where space or efficiency is at a premium.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Most commonly, they are used to represent a simple group of Boolean flags or an ordered sequence of Boolean values.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Bit arrays are used for priority queues, where the bit at index *k* is set if and only if *k* is in the queue; this data structure is used, for example, by the Linux kernel, and benefits strongly from a find-first-zero operation in hardware.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Bit arrays can be used for the allocation of memory pages, inodes, disk sectors, etc.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] In such cases, the term *bitmap* may be used.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] However, this term is frequently used to refer to raster images, which may use multiple bits per pixel.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Another application of bit arrays is the Bloom filter, a probabilistic set data structure that can store large sets in a small space in exchange for a small probability of error.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] It is also possible to build probabilistic hash tables based on bit arrays that accept either false positives or false negatives.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Bit arrays and the operations on them are also important for constructing succinct data structures, which use close to the minimum possible space.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] In this context, operations like finding the *n*th 1 bit or counting the number of 1 bits up to a certain position become important.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Bit arrays are also a useful abstraction for examining streams of compressed data, which often contain elements that occupy portions of bytes or are not byte-aligned.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] For example, the compressed Huffman coding representation of a single 8-bit character can be anywhere from 1 to 255 bits long.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] In information retrieval, bit arrays are a good representation for the posting lists of very frequent terms.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] If we compute the gaps between adjacent values in a list of strictly increasing integers and encode them using unary coding, the result is a bit array with a 1 bit in the *n*th position if and only if *n* is in the list.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The implied probability of a gap of *n* is 1/2*n*.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] This is also the special case of Golomb coding where the parameter M is 1; this parameter is only normally selected when −log(2 − *p*) / log(1 − *p*) ≤ 1, or roughly the term occurs in at least 38% of documents.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Given a big file of IPv4 addresses (more than 100 GB) — we need to count unique addresses.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Bit arrays are widely supported in programming languages, either through dedicated interfaces or more general bit manipulation capabilities.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The APL programming language fully supports bit arrays of arbitrary shape and size as a Boolean datatype distinct from integers.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] All major implementations (Dyalog APL, APL2, APL Next, NARS2000, Gnu APL, etc.) pack the bits densely into whatever size the machine word is.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Bits may be accessed individually via the usual indexing notation (for example, `A[3]`) as well as through all of the usual primitive functions and operators where they are often operated on using a special case algorithm such as summing the bits via a table lookup of bytes.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The C programming language's *bit fields*, pseudo-objects found in structs with size equal to some number of bits, are in fact small bit arrays; they are limited in that they cannot span words.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Although they give a convenient syntax, the bits are still accessed using bytewise operators on most machines, and they can only be defined statically (like C's static arrays, their sizes are fixed at compile-time).
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] It is also a common idiom for C programmers to use words as small bit arrays and access bits of them using bit operators.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] A widely available header file included in the X11 system, `<xtrapbits.h>`, is “a portable way for systems to define bit field manipulation of arrays of bits.” A more explanatory description of aforementioned approach can be found in the comp.lang.c faq.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] In C++, although individual `bool`s typically occupy the same space as a byte or an integer, the STL type `std::vector<bool>` is a partial template specialization in which bits are packed as a space efficiency optimization.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Since bytes (and not bits) are the smallest addressable unit in C++, the `[]` operator does *not* return a reference to an element, but instead returns a proxy reference.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] This might seem a minor point, but it means that `vector<bool>` is *not* a standard STL container, which is why the use of `vector<bool>` is generally discouraged.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Another unique STL class, `std::bitset`, creates a vector of bits fixed at a particular size at compile-time, and in its interface and syntax more resembles the idiomatic use of words as bit sets by C programmers.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] It also has some additional power, such as the ability to efficiently count the number of bits that are set.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Like array, the size of `bitset` must be specified at compile time, and cannot be inferred by the compiler.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The Boost C++ Libraries provides a `boost::dynamic_bitset` class whose size is specified at run-time.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The D programming language provides bit arrays in its standard library, Phobos, in `std.bitmanip`.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] As in C++, the [] operator does not return a reference, since individual bits are not directly addressable on most hardware, but instead returns a `bool`.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] In Java, the class `BitSet` (`java.util.BitSet`) creates a bit array that is then manipulated with functions named after bitwise operators familiar to C programmers.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Unlike the `bitset` in C++, the Java `BitSet` does not have a "size" state (it has an effectively infinite size, initialized with 0 bits); a bit can be set or tested at any index.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] In addition, there is a class `EnumSet` (`java.util.EnumSet`), which represents a Set of values of an enumerated type internally as a bit vector, as a safer alternative to bit fields.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The .NET Framework supplies a `Systems.Collections.BitArray` collection class.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] It stores bits using an array of type `int` (each element in the array usually represents 32 bits).
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The class supports random access and bitwise operators, can be iterated over, and its `Length` property can be changed to grow or truncate it.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Although Standard ML has no support for bit arrays, Standard ML of New Jersey has an extension, the `BitArray` structure, in its SML/NJ Library.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] It is not fixed in size and supports set operations and bit operations, including, unusually, shift operations.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] In Perl, strings can be used as expandable bit arrays.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] They can be manipulated using the usual bitwise operators (`~ | & ^`), and individual bits can be tested and set using the *vec* function.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] In Ruby, one can access (but not set) a bit of an integer (`Fixnum` or `Bignum`) using the bracket operator (`[]`), as if it were an array of bits.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Rust supports using native numeric types as fixed-width bit arrays using bitwise operations.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Third party libraries like `bitvec` provide dedicated interfaces.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Apple's Core Foundation library contains CFBitVector and CFMutableBitVector structures.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] PL/I supports arrays of *bit strings* of arbitrary length, which may be either fixed-length or varying.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The array elements may be *aligned*— each element begins on a byte or word boundary— or *unaligned*— elements immediately follow each other with no padding.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] PL/pgSQL and PostgreSQL's SQL support *bit strings* as native type.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] There are two SQL bit types: bit(*`n`*) and bit varying(*`n`*), where *`n`* is a positive integer.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Hardware description languages such as VHDL, Verilog, and SystemVerilog natively support bit vectors as these are used to model storage elements like flip-flops, hardware busses and hardware signals in general.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] In hardware verification languages such as OpenVera, *e* and SystemVerilog, bit vectors are used to sample values from the hardware models, and to represent data that is transferred to hardware during simulations.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Common Lisp provides multi-dimensional bit arrays.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] A one-dimensional `bit-vector` implementation is provided as a special case of the built-in `array`, acting in a dual capacity as a class and a type specifier.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Bit arrays (and thus bit vectors) relies on the general `make-array` function to be configured with an element type of `bit`, which optionally permits a bit vector to be designated as dynamically resizable.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] The `bit-vector`, however, is not infinite in extent.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] A more restricted `simple-bit-vector` type exists, which explicitly excludes the dynamic characteristics.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Bit vectors are represented as, and can be constructed in a more concise fashion by, the *reader macro* `#**bits*`.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] In addition to the general functions applicable to all arrays, dedicated operations exist for bit arrays.
[src:fenwick-tree/bit-array] Single bits may be accessed and modified using the `bit` and `sbit` functions and an extensive number of logical operations is supported.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] A **Fenwick tree** or **binary indexed tree** **(BIT)** is a data structure that stores an array of values and can efficiently compute prefix sums of the values *and* update the values.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] It also supports an efficient rank-search operation for finding the longest prefix whose sum is no more than a specified value.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Its primary use is operating on the cumulative distribution function of a statistical frequency table which is updated often.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] This structure was proposed by Boris Ryabko in 1989 with a further modification published in 1992.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] It has subsequently become known under the name Fenwick tree after Peter Fenwick, who described this structure in his 1994 article.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] A simple array of values is trivial (constant-time) to update but requires $O(n)$ time to compute a prefix sum or search for a prefix length.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] An array of prefix sums can return a prefix sum in constant time, and search for a prefix length in $O(\log n)$ time, but requires $O(n)$ time to update one of the values.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] A Fenwick tree allows all three operations to be performed in $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] This is achieved by representing the values as a tree with $n+1$ nodes where each node in the tree stores the sum of the values from the index of its parent (exclusive) up to the index of the node (inclusive).
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] The tree itself is implicit and can be stored as an array of n values, with the implicit root node omitted from the array.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] The tree structure allows the operations of value retrieval, value update, prefix sum, and range sum to be performed using only $O(\log n)$ node accesses.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Given an array of values, it is sometimes desirable to calculate the running total of values up to each index according to some associative binary operation (addition on integers being by far the most common).
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Fenwick trees provide a method to query the running total at any index, or prefix sum, while allowing changes to the underlying value array and having all further queries reflect those changes.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Fenwick trees are particularly designed to implement adaptive arithmetic coding, which maintains counts of each symbol produced and needs to convert those to the cumulative probability of a symbol less than a given symbol.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Development of operations it supports were primarily motivated by use in that case.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] A Fenwick tree is an implicit tree where nodes are consecutively numbered, and parent-child relationships are determined by arithmetic on the node indexes.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] An important function in this index arithmetic is the *least significant set bit*.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] This is the greatest power of two which divides an index i .
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] It can be efficiently computed in two's complement arithmetic as $\operatorname {lsb} (i)=i\mathbin {\&} -i$ (where & denotes bitwise AND).
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] A Fenwick tree is most easily understood using a one-based array $A[n]$ with n values.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Using half-open interval syntax, let $A(i,j]=\{A[k]\}_{k=i+1}^{j},$ the range from i (exclusive) to j (inclusive).
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] The corresponding Fenwick array $F[n]$ stores the range sums $\textstyle F[i]=\sum A(i-\operatorname {lsb} (i),i]$ .
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] That is, the sum of $\operatorname {lsb} (i)$ values ending with and including $A[i]$ .
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] A fictitious node 0 is used in some descriptions, but is never actually accessed and need not be explicitly stored. $\operatorname {lsb} (0)=\infty ,$ but the value is never actually needed. $F[0]$ may be considered to contain the sum of the empty range $A(0,0]=\{\}$ with value 0.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] A "Fenwick tree" is actually *three* implicit trees over the same array: the *interrogation tree* used for translating indexes to prefix sums, the *update* tree used for updating elements, and the *search tree* for translating prefix sums to indexes (rank queries).
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] The first two are normally walked upwards, while the third is usually walked downwards.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] The interrogation tree is defined so that the parent of node i is $i-\operatorname {lsb} (i)=i\mathbin {\&} (i-1)$ .
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Each level k of the tree contains nodes with indices corresponding to sums of k distinct powers of 2 (with $k=0$ representing an empty sum 0).
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] To find the prefix sum $A[1]+\cdots +A[i]$ , sum the values in i , its parent, its parent's parent, and so on up to (but not including) the root.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] To compute a range sum $A[i]+\cdots +A[j]$ , subtract the prefix sums for $i-1$ and j .
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] This can be optimized by stopping at their first common ancestor.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] An extreme example is asking for a single entry $A[j]$ .
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] In this case, the common ancestor of j and $i=j-1$ is $j-\operatorname {lsb} (j)$ , so start with $F[j]$ and then, as long as $i\neq j-\operatorname {lsb} (j)$ , subtract $F[i]$ and update `i := i - lsb(i)`.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] The update tree is the mirror image of the interrogation tree.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] The parent of node i is $i+\operatorname {lsb} (i)=(i\mathbin {|} (i-1))+1$ (where | denotes bitwise OR).
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] This conceptual tree is infinite, but only the part with indexes up to n is stored or used.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Excluding the fictitious nodes with indexes greater than n it will be a forest of disjoint trees, one for each bit set in the binary representation of n .
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Here, a node's ancestors are all nodes whose range sums include its own.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] To modify one of the values $A[i]$ , add the change to $F[i]$ , then i 's parent, then its grandparent, and so on, until the index exceeds n .
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Unlike the other two trees, the search tree is a binary tree, arranged in an order Knuth calls a "sideways heap".
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Each node is assigned a height equal to the number of trailing zeros in the binary representation of its index, with the parent and children being the numerically closest index(es) of the adjacent height.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Nodes with odd indexes ( $\operatorname {lsb} (i)=1$ ) are leaves.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Nodes with even indexes have the closest two nodes of the next-lowest index as children, $i\pm \operatorname {lsb} (i)/2$ .
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Node i 's parent in the search tree is $(i-\operatorname {lsb} (i))\mathbin {|} (2\cdot \operatorname {lsb} (i))$ .
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Although this tree is potentially infinite, we may define its root to be the highest *existing* node, whose index is the greatest power of 2 less than or equal to n .
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] It is possible for a node to have a fictitious parent with an index greater than n yet still have an existing grandparent.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] If the example above applied to a 5-node tree, then node 5 would have a fictitious parent 6, but an existing grandparent 4.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] The search tree may be considered a combination of the previous two trees.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] A node's left subtree contains all of its descendants in the update tree, while its right subtree contains all of its descendants in the interrogation tree.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] A node's parent in the search tree is either its interrogation or update parent (depending on whether the node is a right or left child, respectively), and the other type of parent may be found by multiple upward steps in the search tree.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] However, upward traversals in the search tree are uncommon; its primary use is to perform rank queries: given a prefix sum, at what index does it appear?
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] This is done by a *downward* traversal through the search tree.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] During the traversal, three variables are maintained: The current node's index, the rank being sought in the subtree rooted at the current node, and a "fallback index" to be returned if the rank sought is greater than can be found in the subtree.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Initially, the current node is the root, the rank sought is the original query, and the fallback index is a special "overflow" value indicating that the rank is not in the tree.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] Each step, either the current node is a fictitious node (index greater than n ), or we must decide if the position sought is to the left or right of the end of the current node.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] If the rank sought is less than the Fenwick array value $F[i]$ for the current node, we must search its left subtree.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] If it is greater, search its right subtree.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] If it is equal, the direction chosen depends on how you wish to handle searches for sums lying exactly between two nodes.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] The function ${\text{lsb}}(n)$ computes the *least significant set bit* of the given n or, equivalently, the largest power of two that is also a divisor of n .
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] This function can be simply implemented in code through a bitwise AND operation: `lsb(n) = n & (-n)`, assuming two's complement negation.
[src:fenwick-tree/fenwick-tree] One naïve algorithm to construct a Fenwick tree consists of initializing the tree with null values and updating each index individually.
[src:fenwick-tree/order-statistic-tree] Both operations can be performed in *O*(log *n*) worst case time when a self-balancing tree is used as the base data structure.
[src:fenwick-tree/order-statistic-tree] To turn a regular search tree into an order statistic tree, the nodes of the tree need to store one additional value, which is the size of the subtree rooted at that node (i.e., the number of nodes below it).
[src:fenwick-tree/order-statistic-tree] Order-statistic trees can be further amended with bookkeeping information to maintain balance (e.g., tree height can be added to get an order statistic AVL tree, or a color bit to get a red–black order statistic tree).
[src:fenwick-tree/order-statistic-tree] Alternatively, the size field can be used in conjunction with a weight-balancing scheme at no additional storage cost.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Prefix sums are trivial to compute in sequential models of computation, by using the formula *yi* = *y**i* − 1 + *xi* to compute each output value in sequence order.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] However, despite their ease of computation, prefix sums are a useful primitive in certain algorithms such as counting sort, and they form the basis of the **scan** higher-order function in functional programming languages.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Prefix sums have also been much studied in parallel algorithms, both as a test problem to be solved and as a useful primitive to be used as a subroutine in other parallel algorithms.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Abstractly, a prefix sum requires only a binary associative operator ⊕, making it useful for many applications from calculating well-separated pair decompositions of points to string processing.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Mathematically, the operation of taking prefix sums can be generalized from finite to infinite sequences; in that context, a prefix sum is known as a partial sum of a series.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Prefix summation or partial summation form linear operators on the vector spaces of finite or infinite sequences; their inverses are finite difference operators.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] In functional programming terms, the prefix sum may be generalized to any binary operation (not just the addition operation); the higher order function resulting from this generalization is called a **scan**, and it is closely related to the fold operation.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Both the scan and the fold operations apply the given binary operation to the same sequence of values, but differ in that the scan returns the whole sequence of results from the binary operation, whereas the fold returns only the final result.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Programming language and library implementations of scan may be either *inclusive* or *exclusive*.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] In the latter case, implementations either leave *y*0 undefined or accept a separate "*x*−1" value with which to seed the scan.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Either type of scan can be transformed into the other: an inclusive scan can be transformed into an exclusive scan by shifting the array produced by the scan right by one element and inserting the identity value at the left of the array.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Conversely, an exclusive scan be transformed into an inclusive scan by shifting the array produced by the scan left and inserting the sum of the last element of the scan and the last element of the input array at the right of the array.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The directive-based OpenMP parallel programming model supports both inclusive and exclusive scan support beginning with Version 5.0.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] There are two key algorithms for computing a prefix sum in parallel.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The first offers a shorter span and more parallelism but is not work-efficient.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The second is work-efficient but requires double the span and offers less parallelism.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] In the above, the notation $x_{j}^{i}$ means the value of the *j*th element of array *x* in timestep *i*.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] With a single processor this algorithm would run in *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] However, if the machine has at least *n* processors to perform the inner loop in parallel, the algorithm as a whole runs in *O*(log *n*) time, the number of iterations of the outer loop.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] A work-efficient parallel prefix sum can be computed by the following steps.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] After the first value, each successive number *yi* is either copied from a position half as far through the w sequence, or is the previous value added to one value in the x sequence.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] If the input sequence has n steps, then the recursion continues to a depth of *O*(log *n*), which is also the bound on the parallel running time of this algorithm.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Each of the preceding algorithms runs in *O*(log *n*) time.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] However, the former takes exactly log2 *n* steps, while the latter requires 2 log2 *n* − 2 steps.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] For the 16-input examples illustrated, Algorithm 1 is 12-way parallel (49 units of work divided by a span of 4) while Algorithm 2 is only 4-way parallel (26 units of work divided by a span of 6).
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] However, Algorithm 2 is work-efficient—it performs only a constant factor (2) of the amount of work required by the sequential algorithm—while Algorithm 1 is work-inefficient—it performs asymptotically more work (a logarithmic factor) than is required sequentially.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Consequently, Algorithm 1 is likely to perform better when abundant parallelism is available, but Algorithm 2 is likely to perform better when parallelism is more limited.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Parallel algorithms for prefix sums can often be generalized to other scan operations on associative binary operations, and they can also be computed efficiently on modern parallel hardware such as a GPU.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The idea of building in hardware a functional unit dedicated to computing multi-parameter prefix-sum was patented by Uzi Vishkin.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Asymptotically this method takes approximately two read operations and one write operation per item.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] An implementation of a parallel prefix sum algorithm, like other parallel algorithms, has to take the parallelization architecture of the platform into account.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] More specifically, multiple algorithms exist which are adapted for platforms working on shared memory as well as algorithms which are well suited for platforms using distributed memory, relying on message passing as the only form of interprocess communication.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The following algorithm assumes a shared memory machine model; all processing elements (PEs) have access to the same memory.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] A version of this algorithm is implemented in the Multi-Core Standard Template Library (MCSTL), a parallel implementation of the C++ standard template library which provides adapted versions for parallel computing of various algorithms.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] In order to concurrently calculate the prefix sum over n data elements with p processing elements, the data is divided into $p+1$ blocks, each containing ${\frac {n}{p+1}}$ elements (for simplicity we assume that $p+1$ divides n).
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Note, that although the algorithm divides the data into $p+1$ blocks, only p processing elements run in parallel at a time.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] In a first sweep, each PE calculates a local prefix sum for its block.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The last block does not need to be calculated, since these prefix sums are only calculated as offsets to the prefix sums of succeeding blocks and the last block is by definition not succeeded.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The p offsets which are stored in the last position of each block are accumulated in a prefix sum of their own and stored in their succeeding positions.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] For p being a small number, it is faster to do this sequentially, for a large p, this step could be done in parallel as well.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] This time the first block does not have to be processed, since it does not need to account for the offset of a preceding block.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] However, in this sweep the last block is included instead and the prefix sums for each block are calculated taking the prefix sum block offsets calculated in the previous sweep into account.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The Hypercube Prefix Sum Algorithm is well adapted for distributed memory platforms and works with the exchange of messages between the processing elements.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] It assumes to have $p=2^{d}$ processor elements (PEs) participating in the algorithm equal to the number of corners in a d-dimensional hypercube.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Throughout the algorithm, each PE is seen as a corner in a hypothetical hyper cube with knowledge of the total prefix sum σ as well as the prefix sum x of all elements up to itself (according to the ordered indices among the PEs), both in its own hypercube.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] In a d-dimensional hyper cube with $2^{d}$ PEs at the corners, the algorithm has to be repeated d times to have the $2^{d}$ zero-dimensional hyper cubes be unified into one d-dimensional hyper cube.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Assuming a duplex communication model where the σ of two adjacent PEs in different hyper cubes can be exchanged in both directions in one communication step, this means $d=\log _{2}p$ communication startups.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The Pipelined Binary Tree Algorithm is another algorithm for distributed memory platforms which is specifically well suited for large message sizes.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Like the hypercube algorithm, it assumes a special communication structure.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The processing elements (PEs) are hypothetically arranged in a binary tree (e.g. a Fibonacci Tree) with infix numeration according to their index within the PEs.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Communication on such a tree always occurs between parent and child nodes.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The infix numeration ensures that for any given PEj, the indices of all nodes reachable by its left subtree $\color {Blue}{[l\dots j-1]}$ are less than j and the indices $\color {Blue}{[j+1\dots r]}$ of all nodes in the right subtree are greater than j.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The parent's index is greater than any of the indices in PEj's subtree if PEj is a left child and smaller if PEj is a right child.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Note the distinction between subtree-local and total prefix sums.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The points two, three and four can lead to believe they would form a circular dependency, but this is not the case.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Lower level PEs might require the total prefix sum of higher level PEs to calculate their total prefix sum, but higher level PEs only require subtree local prefix sums to calculate their total prefix sum.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The root node as highest level node only requires the local prefix sum of its left subtree to calculate its own prefix sum.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Each PE on the path from PE0 to the root PE only requires the local prefix sum of its left subtree to calculate its own prefix sum, whereas every node on the path from PEp-1 (last PE) to the PEroot requires the total prefix sum of its parent to calculate its own total prefix sum.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Note that the algorithm is run in parallel at each PE and the PEs will block upon receive until their children/parents provide them with packets.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] If the message m of length n can be divided into k packets and the operator ⨁ can be used on each of the corresponding message packets separately, pipelining is possible.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] If the algorithm is used without pipelining, there are always only two levels (the sending PEs and the receiving PEs) of the binary tree at work while all other PEs are waiting.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Assuming a communication startup time of $T_{\mathrm {start} }$ and a bytewise transmission time of $T_{\mathrm {byte} }$ , upward and downward phase are limited to $(2\log _{2}p-2)(T_{\mathrm {start} }+n\cdot T_{\mathrm {byte} })$ in a non pipelined scenario.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The algorithm can further be optimised by making use of full-duplex or telephone model communication and overlapping the upward and the downward phase.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] When a data set may be updated dynamically, it may be stored in a Fenwick tree data structure.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] This structure allows both the lookup of any individual prefix sum value and the modification of any array value in logarithmic time per operation.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] However, an earlier 1982 paper presents a data structure called Partial Sums Tree (see Section 5.1) that appears to overlap Fenwick trees; in 1982 the term prefix-sum was not yet as common as it is today.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] For higher-dimensional arrays, the summed area table provides a data structure based on prefix sums for computing sums of arbitrary rectangular subarrays.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] This can be a helpful primitive in image convolution operations.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Counting sort is an integer sorting algorithm that uses the prefix sum of a histogram of key frequencies to calculate the position of each key in the sorted output array.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] It runs in linear time for integer keys that are smaller than the number of items, and is frequently used as part of radix sort, a fast algorithm for sorting integers that are less restricted in magnitude.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] An early application of parallel prefix sum algorithms was in the design of binary adders, Boolean circuits that can add two n-bit binary numbers.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] In this application, the sequence of carry bits of the addition can be represented as a scan operation on the sequence of pairs of input bits, using the majority function to combine the previous carry with these two bits.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Each bit of the output number can then be found as the exclusive or of two input bits with the corresponding carry bit.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] By using a circuit that performs the operations of the parallel prefix sum algorithm, it is possible to design an adder that uses *O*(*n*) logic gates and *O*(log *n*) time steps.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] In the parallel random access machine model of computing, prefix sums can be used to simulate parallel algorithms that assume the ability for multiple processors to access the same memory cell at the same time, on parallel machines that forbid simultaneous access.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] In Guy Blelloch's Ph.D. thesis, parallel prefix operations form part of the formalization of the data parallelism model provided by machines such as the Connection Machine.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The Connection Machine CM-1 and CM-2 provided a hypercubic network on which the Algorithm 1 above could be implemented, whereas the CM-5 provided a dedicated network to implement Algorithm 2.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The reverse operation, decoding a Gray-coded value x into a binary number, is more complicated, but can be expressed as the prefix sum of the bits of x, where each summation operation within the prefix sum is performed modulo two.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] A prefix sum of this type may be performed efficiently using the bitwise Boolean operations available on modern computers, by computing the exclusive or of x with each of the numbers formed by shifting x to the left by a number of bits that is a power of two.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Parallel prefix (using multiplication as the underlying associative operation) can also be used to build fast algorithms for parallel polynomial interpolation.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] In particular, it can be used to compute the divided difference coefficients of the Newton form of the interpolation polynomial.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] This prefix based approach can also be used to obtain the generalized divided differences for (confluent) Hermite interpolation as well as for parallel algorithms for Vandermonde systems.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Parallel prefix algorithms can also be used for temporal parallelization of Recursive Bayesian estimation methods, including Bayesian filters, Kalman filters, as well as the corresponding smoothers.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The core idea is that, for example, the solutions to the Bayesian/Kalman filtering problems are written in terms of a suitably defined associative filtering operator such that the prefix "sums" of the filtering operator gives the filtering solution.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] This allows parallel prefix algorithms to be applied to compute the filtering and smoothing solutions.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] A similar idea also works for the parallelization of a class of probabilistic differential equation solvers in the context of Probabilistic numerics.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] In the context of Optimal control, parallel prefix algorithms can be used for parallelization of Bellman equation and Hamilton–Jacobi–Bellman equations (HJB equations), including their Linear–quadratic regulator special cases.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Here, the idea is that we can define an associative operator for a combination of conditional value functions (conditioned on the end-point), and the prefix sums of this operator give solutions to the Bellman equations or HJB equations.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Prefix sum is used for load balancing as a low-cost algorithm to distribute the work between multiple processors, where the overriding goal is achieving an equal amount of work on each processor.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] The algorithms uses an array of weights representing the amount of work required for each item.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] After the prefix sum is calculated, the work item i is sent for processing to the processor unit with the number [ ⁠prefixSumValue*i*/ totalWork / numberOfProcessors⁠ ].
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Graphically this corresponds to an operation where the amount of work in each item is represented by the length of a linear segment, all segments are sequentially placed onto a line and the result cut into number of pieces, corresponding to the number of the processors.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Below is a lookup table of quarter squares with the remainder discarded for the digits 0 through 18; this allows for the multiplication of numbers up to 9×9.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] If, for example, you wanted to multiply 9 by 3, you observe that the sum and difference are 12 and 6 respectively.
[src:fenwick-tree/prefix-sum] Looking both those values up on the table yields 36 and 9, the difference of which is 27, which is the product of 9 and 3.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] In computer science, a **range minimum query** (**RMQ**) solves the problem of finding the minimal value in a sub-array of an array of comparable objects.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] Range minimum queries have several use cases in computer science, such as the lowest common ancestor problem and the longest common prefix problem (LCP).
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] Given an array *A*[1 … *n*] of n objects taken from a totally ordered set, such as integers, the range minimum query RMQ*A*(*l*,*r*) =arg min *A*[*k*] (with 1 ≤ *l* ≤ *k* ≤ *r* ≤ *n*) returns the position of the minimal element in the specified sub-array *A*[*l* … *r*].
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] In a typical setting, the array A is static, i.e., elements are not inserted or deleted during a series of queries, and the queries to be answered on-line (i.e., the whole set of queries are not known in advance to the algorithm).
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] In this case a suitable preprocessing of the array into a data structure ensures faster query answering.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] A naive solution is to precompute all possible queries, i.e. the minimum of all sub-arrays of A, and store these in an array B such that *B*[*i*, *j*] = min(*A*[*i*…*j*]); then a range min query can be solved in constant time by array lookup in B.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] There are Θ(*n*²) possible queries for a length-n array, and the answers to these can be computed in Θ(*n*²) time by dynamic programming.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] As in the solution above, answering queries in constant time will be achieved by pre-computing results.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] However, the array will store pre-computed range minimum queries not for every range [*i*, *j*], but only for ranges whose size is a power of two.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] There are O(log *n*) such queries for each start position i, so the size of the dynamic programming table B is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] After this pre-computing step, a query RMQ*A*(*l*,*r*) can now be answered in constant time by splitting it into two separate queries: one is the pre-computed query with range from l to the largest memoized value smaller than r.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] The other is the query of an interval of the same length that has r as its right boundary.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] These intervals may overlap, but since we are trying to compute the minimum rather than, for example, the sum of the numbers in the array, this does not matter.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] The overall result can thus be obtained, after the linearithmic time pre-computing, in constant time: the two queries can be answered in constant time and the only thing left to do is to choose the smaller of the two results.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] This solution does pre-computation in *O*(*n*) time.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] Its data structures use *O*(*n*) space and its data structures can be used to answer queries in logarithmic time.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] The array is first conceptually divided into blocks of size *s* = ⁠log *n*/4⁠.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] Then the minimum for each block can be computed in *O*(*n*) time overall and the minima are stored in a new array.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] For example, using the array *A* = [0,5,2,5,4,3,1,6,3] and a block size of 3 (for illustrative purposes only) yields the minimum array *A'* = [0,3,1].
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] Using the solution above, the sub-queries inside the blocks that are not fully contained in the query still need to be answered in constant time.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] There are at most two of those blocks: the block containing l and the block containing r.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] Constant time is achieved by storing the Cartesian trees for all the blocks in the array.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] For every such tree, the possible result for all queries need to be stored.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] This comes down to *s*2 or *O*(log2 *n*) entries.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] This means the overall size of the table is *O*(*n*).
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] To look up results efficiently, the Cartesian tree (row) corresponding to a specific block must be addressable in constant time.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] The solution is to store the results for all trees in an array and find a unique projection from binary trees to integers to address the entries.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] This can be achieved by doing a breadth-first-search through the tree and adding leaf nodes so that every existing node in the Cartesian tree has exactly two children.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] The integer is then generated by representing every inner node as a 0-bit and every leaf as a 1-bit in a bit-word (by traversing the tree in level-order again).
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] This leads to a size of ⁠log *n*/4⁠ for every tree.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] To enable random access in constant time to any tree, the trees not contained in the original array need to be included as well.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] An array with indices of ⁠log *n*/4⁠ bits length has size 2⁠log *n*/4⁠ = *O*(*n*).
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] RMQs are used as a tool for many tasks in exact and approximate string matching.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] Several applications can be found in Fischer and Heun (2007).
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] RMQs can be used to solve the lowest common ancestor problem and are used as a tool for many tasks in exact and approximate string matching.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] The LCA query LCA*S*(*v*, *w*) of a rooted tree *S* = (*V*, *E*) and two nodes *v*, *w* ∈ *V* returns the deepest node u (which may be v or w) on paths from the root to both w and v.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] Gabow, Bentley, and Tarjan (1984) showed that the LCA Problem can be reduced in linear time to the RMQ problem.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] It follows that, like the RMQ problem, the LCA problem can be solved in constant time and linear space.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] In the context of text indexing, RMQs can be used to find the LCP (longest common prefix), where LCP*T*(*i*, *j*) computes the LCP of the suffixes that start at indexes i and j in T.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] To do this we first compute the suffix array A, and the inverse suffix array *A*−1.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] We then compute the LCP array H giving the LCP of adjacent suffixes in A.
[src:fenwick-tree/range-minimum-query] Once these data structures are computed, and RMQ preprocessing is complete, the length of the general LCP can be computed in constant time by the formula: LCP(*i*, *j*) = RMQH(*A*-1[*i*] + 1, *A*-1[*j*]), where we assume for simplicity that *A*-1[*i*] + 1 <= *A*-1[*j*] (otherwise swap).
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] In computer science, the **segment tree** is a data structure used for storing information about intervals or segments.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] It allows querying which of the stored segments contain a given point.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] A similar data structure is the interval tree.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] A segment tree for a set I of *n* intervals uses *O*(*n* log *n*) storage and can be built in *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Segment trees support searching for all the intervals that contain a query point in time *O*(log *n* + *k*), *k* being the number of retrieved intervals or segments.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Applications of the segment tree are in the areas of computational geometry, geographic information systems and machine learning.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] The segment tree can be generalized to higher dimension spaces.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Let I be a set of intervals, or segments.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Let *p*1, *p*2, ..., *pm* be the list of distinct interval endpoints, sorted from left to right.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Consider the partitioning of the real line induced by those points.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] The regions of this partitioning are called *elementary intervals*.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] That is, the list of elementary intervals consists of open intervals between two consecutive endpoints *pi* and *p**i*+1, alternated with closed intervals consisting of a single endpoint.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Single points are treated themselves as intervals because the answer to a query is not necessarily the same at the interior of an elementary interval and its endpoints.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] A segment tree from the set of segments I, can be built as follows.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] First, the endpoints of the intervals in I are sorted.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] The elementary intervals are obtained from that.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Then, a balanced binary tree is built on the elementary intervals, and for each node *v* it is determined the interval Int(*v*) it represents.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] It remains to compute the canonical subsets for the nodes.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] To achieve this, the intervals in I are inserted one by one into the segment tree.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] The complete construction operation takes *O*(*n* log *n*) time, *n* being the number of segments in I.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Visiting every node takes constant time (assuming that canonical subsets are stored in a simple data structure like a linked list).
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] When we visit node *v*, we either store *X* at *v*, or Int(*v*) contains an endpoint of *X*.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] As proved above, an interval is stored at most twice at each level of the tree.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] There is also at most one node at every level whose corresponding interval contains *x*, and one node whose interval contains *x′*.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] So, at most four nodes per level are visited.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Since there are *O*(log *n*) levels, the total cost of the insertion is *O*(log *n*).
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] A query for a segment tree receives a point *qx*(should be one of the leaves of tree), and retrieves a list of all the segments stored which contain the point *qx*.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] In a segment tree that contains *n* intervals, those containing a given query point can be reported in *O*(log *n* + *k*) time, where *k* is the number of reported intervals.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] The query algorithm visits one node per level of the tree, so *O*(log *n*) nodes in total.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] On the other hand, at a node *v*, the segments in I are reported in *O*(1 + *kv*) time, where *kv* is the number of intervals at node *v*, reported.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] The sum of all the *kv* for all nodes *v* visited, is *k*, the number of reported segments.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] A segment tree *T* on a set I of *n* intervals uses *O*(*n* log *n*) storage.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Let *v*1, *v*2, *v*3 be the three nodes at the same depth, numbered from left to right; and let p(*v*) be the parent node of any given node *v*.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] This means that [*x*, *x′*] spans the whole interval from the left endpoint of Int(*v*1) to the right endpoint of Int(*v*3).
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Note that all segments at a particular level are non-overlapping and ordered from left to right: this is true by construction for the level containing the leaves, and the property is not lost when moving from any level to the one above it by combining pairs of adjacent segments.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Now either parent(*v*2) = parent(*v*1), or the former is to the right of the latter (edges in the tree do not cross).
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] In the first case, Int(parent(*v*2))'s leftmost point is the same as Int(*v*1)'s leftmost point; in the second case, Int(parent(*v*2))'s leftmost point is to the right of Int(parent(*v*1))'s rightmost point, and therefore also to the right of Int(*v*1)'s rightmost point.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] In both cases, Int(parent(*v*2)) begins at or to the right of Int(*v*1)'s leftmost point.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Similar reasoning shows that Int(parent(*v*2)) ends at or to the left of Int(*v*3)'s rightmost point.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] Int(parent(*v*2)) must therefore be contained in [*x*, *x′*]; hence, [*x*, *x′*] will not be stored at *v*2.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] The segment tree can be generalized to higher dimension spaces, in the form of multi-level segment trees.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] In higher dimensional versions, the segment tree stores a collection of axis-parallel (hyper-)rectangles, and can retrieve the rectangles that contain a given query point.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] The structure uses *O*(*n* log*d* *n*) storage, and answers queries in *O*(log*d* *n*) time.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] The use of fractional cascading lowers the query time bound by a logarithmic factor.
[src:fenwick-tree/segment-tree] The use of the interval tree on the deepest level of associated structures lowers the storage bound by a logarithmic factor.
